location: Burlington/Mebane, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
For sale or trade is a Smith & Wesson Victory in 38 Special. This revolver was one made during World War 2 originally part of the Lend Lease program with Great Britain. However, once the US entered the war S&W retooled their factory to make the revolver in 38 Special. This isn't one of the ones that was originally 38 S&W and made into 38 Special by Parker Hale after the war. The revolver was reparked sometime in its lifetime, done before I got it in my collection several years ago. All numbers match on the revolver, with the exception of the grips. I got this in a trade awhile back, and as time goes on, I'm realizing I really have no use whatsoever for it, so I'd like to sell or trade it for something more useful to me.

The barrel has had a muzzle break drilled into it - it hasn't been reblued or anything, so it's a bit ugly, but it works. Bore is good, rifling is strong. postcontent:
(5) 20 round bundles of Russian manufactured 7N1 Sniper ammo.    

It's loaded in annealed copper washed steel cases with a specially designed 152 grain boat tail bullet.    

 Bullet has a steel core followed by a dead air space with a lead knocker in the base.     

When bullet hits it's target the lead knocker shifts forward destabilizing the bullet resulting in a devastating wound.     

This ammo was specifically designed for the Dragunov, but it's excellent for Mosins too.     

Accuracy has been far better in all my rifles than the standard light ball ammo being sold today.    

Head stamp 188-97 (LVE 1997)    

Notice the Cyrillic word for sniper is printed on the outside of each bundle.    

There are no other unique identifiers on the ammo itself which is to protect the identity of the snipers who use this ammo.

40 rounds Hungarian Silver/Yellow tip.This ammo has a 182 grain steel core bullet.

It also shoots a good deal more accurately in 

20 rounds East German M39 ammo.This ammo has an all black color 124 grain steel jacketed, steel core bullet. 20 rounds Bulgarian brass case with a 149 grain magnetic bullet. Ammo is from the mid 50's but looks like it was made yesterday. It's super clean ammo and I've always felt brass cased ammo operated more smoothly than the steel case stuff.

20 rounds Green Tracer. Pretty much the same as the red above but trace is a bright green color. This ammo is also loaded on 4 Mosin clips.

title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 70 Short Rifle Pre-War Carbine
postcontent: Winchester model 70. Serial Number 21361 was produced BEFORE WW2 and was produced as a factory 20 inch barrel SHORT RIFLE in 1939. Caliber is 30 Govt'06 and there are NO Non-Factory holes or alterations. The rear bridge has NEVER been drilled and tapped. Original sights are present and the front sight is an integral part of the barrel so it is impossible to fake. Early features including the clover leaf tang and early style safety. Excellent bore and mechanics. Nearly all of the original blue remains and this short rifle has seen limited and careful use. Solid stock with strong original checkering and original butt plate. Perhaps a light coat of oil has been applied to the stock long ago. It looks great with excellent wood to metal fit. These factory short rifle model 70's are perhaps one of the most difficult variations to find especially with NO extra holes in the rear bridge as most were scoped up over the years. This is a great model 70 in collector condition sure to appreciate in value.
